— office_dataset

This databse contains data of the 200 respondents and their choice of preferences when it comes to buy the office equipment.

Variable Description
‘respondent_id’ An identifier for our observations
‘variety_of_choice’ Importance of this attribute on a 0-10 scale
‘electronics’ Importance of this attribute on a 0-10 scale
‘furniture’ Importance of this attribute on a 0-10 scale
‘quality_of_service’ Importance of this attribute on a 0-10 scale
‘low_prices’ Importance of this attribute on a 0-10 scale
‘return_policy’ Importance of this attribute on a 0-10 scale

Target Variables - Attributes of target audience.

‘professional’ | Whether the respondent is a professional or not (e.g., student) ‘income’ | Gross annual income expressed in thousands of pound sterling ‘age’ | Respondents’ age in years

Q2 - Start (Creating tibble/dataframe, normalizing the dataset and calculating minimumn & maximum values)

Now, we need to normalize our data before we run the clustering algorithms. Let us go ahead and normalize our data. Make sure you turn the output into a tibble by using the as.tibble function.

Now, create a normalized data frame called office_normalized_dataset by running the following commands:

office_norm<- scale(office[, c(
                           "variety_of_choice",
                           "electronics",
                           "furniture",
                           "quality_of_service",
                           "low_prices",
                           "return_policy"
                           )]) %>% 
  as_tibble() # convert to tibble

We are now going to check whether all the variables now have mean zero by using the mean function. For example, let’s check the variables furniture and electronics:

furniture_mean <- mean(office_norm$furniture)
electronics_mean <- mean(office_norm$electronics)

Let’s now check which variable has the smallest minimum value and which variables has the largest maximum value in the normalized data set. We can do this by using the summary function on office_normalized.

summary(office_norm)

Q3 - Hierarchical Clustering

Now let’s compute the distances between data points (using euclidean distance).

# compute distances
distances <- dist(office_norm, 
                  method = "euclidean") # use Euclidean

# print the distances between the first 5 customers
as.matrix(distances)[1:5, 1:5] 
         1        2        3        4        5
1 0.000000 3.122933 4.066279 3.654938 3.203876
2 3.122933 0.000000 2.795657 3.229408 3.434497
3 4.066279 2.795657 0.000000 1.618520 3.959120
4 3.654938 3.229408 1.618520 0.000000 3.593200
5 3.203876 3.434497 3.959120 3.593200 0.000000

Then let’s run the hierarchical clustering algorithm (using method = "ward.D") on the normalized data. It may take a few minutes for the command to finish since the dataset has a large number of observations for hierarchical clustering.

# run the algorithm and store the result to an object
h_clust <- hclust(distances, method = "ward.D2")

Then, plot the dendrogram of the hierarchical clustering process.

plot(h_clust)

Then, suppose that after looking at the dendrogram and discussing with the marketing department, the office decides to proceed with 6 clusters. So, divide the data points into 6 clusters by using the cutree function.

Q4 - Creating 6 cluster solution

# plot the dendogram again
plot(h_clust)

# now draw rectangles highlighting the clusters
rect.hclust(h_clust, k = 6, border = "purple")

# create a six-cluster solution
hclut_obs <- cutree(h_clust, k = 6)

table(hclut_obs)
hclut_obs
 1  2  3  4  5  6 
59  8 52 17 35 29

So now, after plotting the dendrogram in six cluster solution. we can come to know the number of observations found in each cluster. There are 59 data points in 1st cluster. There are 8 data points in 2nd cluster. There are 52 data points in 3rd cluster. There are 17 data points in 4th cluster. There are 35 data points in 5th cluster. There are 29 data points in 6th cluster.

Q5 - Calculating Average values(mean) & flexClust to compare and create segmentation profile plots.

We can now compare the average values in each of the variables for the 5 clusters (the centroids of the clusters). It is better if we compute the average values of the un-normalized dataset so that it is easier to interpret.

First let’s add the cluster assignment to the un-normalized data set.

office_cw <- office %>% 
  mutate(hclut_obs = hclut_obs)

Then we can group by cluster and calculate the average values in each of the variables.

office_norm %>%
  mutate(hclut_obs = factor(hclut_obs)) %>%
  group_by(hclut_obs) %>% # group by cluster
  mutate(n=n())%>%
  summarise_all(~mean(.x)) %>% # calculate the mean per group 
  mutate(prop=n/sum(n))%>%
  print(width = Inf) # prints all variables (all columns)

From the table output, cluster 1 corresponds to cluster 5 in the hierarchial observations. cluster 2 corresponds to cluster 1 in the hierarchial observations. cluster 3 corresponds to cluster 2 in the hierarchial observations. cluster 4 corresponds to cluster 3 in the hierarchial observations. cluster 5 corresponds to cluster 4 in the hierarchial observations. cluster 6 corresponds to cluster 6 in the hierarchial observations.

# There is a huge difference in results of both as.kcca and hclust procedure.

# run the following command in case the barchart command won't produce a plot

# dev.off() 

barchart(h_clust_flex, main = "Segment Profiles")

# Q7

6 cluster’s solution is having values as 8 in one of the segments which is very low. whereas, in 5 cluster solutions, comparatively the lower values is 17. so on comparison basis, it is better to go with 5 cluster solutions.

Q11 - Observations from cluster

Cluster 1

First, let’s focus our attention to Cluster 1 (i.e., Cluster 4 in the segmentation profiles plot). This cluster is having larger values of target audiences who are satisified with electronics, quality of service, return policy. whereas they are not satisfied with variety of choice, low prices and furniture. because they are having low average values.

This cluster segmentation can be used to target audiences to improve sales in electronics, quality of service and return policy.

Cluster 2

Now turn our attention to Cluster 2 (i.e., Cluster 1 in the segmentation profiles plot). Cluster 1 seg plot is having large average values in variety of choice, electronics, furniture and it almost meets low prices. whereas they are not satisfied with quality of service, return policy.

Cluster 3

Let’s now look at Cluster 3 (i.e., Cluster 2 in the segmentation profiles plot).cluster 2 seg plot is having audiences having higher rating in variety of choice, furniture and electronics.

Cluster 4

Cluster 4 (i.e., Cluster 3 in the segmentation profiles plot). cluster 3 is having respondents having higher satisfaction in quality of service, return policy but with low price.

This provides insights of these audiences tends to buy if the products are of low prices.

Low average values - electronics, furniture, variety of choice, quality of service.

Cluster 5

Finally, Cluster 5 (i.e., Cluster 5 in the segmentation profiles plot). cluster 5 seg plot contains respondents having higher satisfaction only in quality of service.
